similar law in 1917, id. at 150, and Michigan forbade possession
in 1929, id. at 161. A 1923 Ohio law prohibited sale or
possession with intent to sell, id. at 242; Rhode Island
prohibited sale in 1918, id. at 263; and Vermont barred sale
without a prescription in 1915, id. at 296. </p>

<p>31 Ch. 363, [1914] N.Y. Laws 1120. The first narcotics
legislation in New York was enacted in 1893. Ch. 661, art. XII,
208, 11893] N.Y. Laws 1561. The 1893 law provided that no
prescription containing opium, morphine, cocaine or chloral could
be filled more than once. Two years later, the legislature
enacted a provision requiring that the effect of narcotics on the
human system be taught in the public schools. Ch. 1041, 1,
[18951 N.Y. Laws 972. In 1897, a law was passed making it a
felony to possess any narcotic &quot;with intent to administer
the same or cause the same to be administered to another&quot;
without his consent. Ch. 42,  1, [1897] N.Y. Laws 21. The first
provision aimed at the sale of narcotics was passed in 1907 and
provided that the sale or distribution of cocaine without a
prescription was unlawful. Ch. 424, @ 1, [ 1907] N.Y. Laws 879.
This provision was subsequently amended to provide for the
keeping of records of sales and of transactions between dealers.
Ch. 470,  2, [1913] N.Y. Laws 984; ch. 131,  1, [1910] N.Y.
Laws 231; ch. 277,  1, [1908] N.Y. Laws 764. </p>

